<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="409">
Etymology Gr 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181865" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="drepanon">drepanon</taxonomicName>
, sickle, alluding to the propodeal spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="409">
DIAGNOSIS Similar to the Dominican endemic 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181881" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole harlequina Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole harlequina Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="harlequina">harlequina</taxonomicName>
, differing from it and all other 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole Westwood" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
as follows. Major: propodeal spines very thick, curved, sickle-shaped, and much longer than the propodeal basal face anterior to them; head and body bicolored as depicted; all of dorsal surface of head except for occipital margin carinulate and weakly rugulose; head slightly broader than long; petiolar peduncle very long; postpetiole from above diamond-shaped.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="409">Minor: propodeal spines very thick, curved, and sickle-shaped, much longer than the propodeal basal face anterior to them; body concolorous medium brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="409">Measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 1.04, HL 1.02, SL 0.70, EL 0.14, PW 0.50. Paratype minor: HW 0.48, HL 0.52, SL 0.64, EL 0.08, PW 0.32.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="409">Color Major: body medium brown except for the front of the head (as depicted), as well as dorsum of promesonotum and anterior half of first gastral tergite, which are brownish yellow.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="409">Minor: body concolorous medium brown, appendages light to yellowish brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="409">
Range 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181865" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="drepanon">P. drepanon</taxonomicName>
is evidently an endemic of the Dominican Republic; a second collection was made by P. S. Ward 22 km north of Pedemales, 18AÃ‚Â°09TN* 71AÃ‚Â°35'W, 1600 m. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181865" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole drepanon Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="409" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="drepanon">P. drepanon</taxonomicName>
might also occur in Haiti, especially since the type locality is close to the border.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
